# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: winston-logging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:winston-logging/api-console] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] The **`console`** object provides access to the debugging console (e.g., the Web console in Firefox).
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Implementations of the console API may differ between runtimes.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] In particular, some console methods may work differently or not work at all in some online editors and IDEs.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] To see the behavior described in this documentation, try the methods in your browser's developer tools, although even here, there are some differences between browsers.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] The `console` object is available in any global scope.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Log an error message to console if the first argument is `false`.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Log the number of times this line has been called with the given label.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Resets the value of the counter with the given label.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Outputs a message to the console with the debug log level.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Displays an interactive listing of the properties of a specified JavaScript object.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] This listing lets you use disclosure triangles to examine the contents of child objects.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Displays an XML/HTML Element representation of the specified object if possible or the JavaScript Object view if it is not possible.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Outputs a message to the console with the error log level.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Creates a new inline group, indenting all following output by another level.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] To move back out a level, call `console.groupEnd()`.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] However, unlike `console.group()` this starts with the inline group collapsed requiring the use of a disclosure button to expand it.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Outputs a message to the console with the info log level.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Starts the browser's built-in profiler (for example, the Firefox performance tool).
[src:winston-logging/api-console] You can specify an optional name for the profile.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] You can see the resulting profile in the browser's performance tool (for example, the Firefox performance tool).
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Starts a timer with a name specified as an input parameter.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Up to 10,000 simultaneous timers can run on a given page.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Stops the specified timer and logs the elapsed time in milliseconds since it started.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Logs the value of the specified timer to the console.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Adds a marker to the browser performance tool's timeline (Chrome or Firefox).
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Outputs a message to the console with the warning log level.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] The console's most frequently used feature is logging text and other data.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] There are several categories of output you can generate using the `console.log()`, `console.info()`, `console.warn()`, `console.error()`, or `console.debug()` methods.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Each of these results in output styled differently in the log, and you can use the filtering controls provided by your browser to view only the kinds of output that interest you.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] The browser will display as much information about the object as it can and wishes to.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] For example, private state of the object may be displayed too.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Certain types of objects, such as DOM elements or functions, may also be displayed in a special way.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Information about an object is lazily retrieved.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] This means that the log message shows the content of an object at the time when it's first viewed, not when it was logged.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] However, if you expand the object's details, you will see `prop: 123`.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] If you are going to mutate your object and you want to prevent the logged information from being updated, you can deep-clone the object before logging it.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] There are other alternatives that work in browsers, such as `structuredClone()`, which are more effective at cloning different types of objects.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] The first parameter to the logging methods can be a string containing zero or more substitution strings.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Each substitution string is replaced by the corresponding argument value.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Outputs a JavaScript object in the "optimally useful formatting" style, for example DOM elements may be displayed the same way as they would appear in the element inspector.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Outputs a JavaScript object in the "generic JavaScript object formatting" style, usually in the form of an expandable tree.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Applies CSS style rules to all following text.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Some browsers may implement additional format specifiers.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] For example, Safari and Firefox support the C-style precision formatting `%.<precision>f`.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] For example `console.log("Foo %.2f", 1.1)` will output the number to 2 decimal places: `Foo 1.10`, while `console.log("Foo %.2d", 1.1)` will output the number as two significant figures with a leading 0: `Foo 01`.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Each of these pulls the next argument after the format string off the parameter list.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] The text before the directive will not be affected, but the text after the directive will be styled using the CSS declarations in the parameter.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] You can use nested groups to help organize your output by visually combining related material.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] To create a new nested block, call `console.group()`.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] The `console.groupCollapsed()` method is similar but creates the new block collapsed, requiring the use of a disclosure button to open it for reading.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] To exit the current group, call `console.groupEnd()`.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] You can start a timer to calculate the duration of a specific operation.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] To start one, call the `console.time()` method, giving it a name as the only parameter.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] To stop the timer, and to get the elapsed time in milliseconds, just call the `console.timeEnd()` method, again passing the timer's name as the parameter.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Up to 10,000 timers can run simultaneously on a given page.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] Notice that the timer's name is displayed both when the timer is started and when it's stopped.
[src:winston-logging/api-console] The console object also supports outputting a stack trace; this will show you the call path taken to reach the point at which you call `console.trace()`.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] The **`JSON`** namespace object contains static methods for parsing values from and converting values to JavaScript Object Notation (JSON).
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] Unlike most global objects, `JSON` is not a constructor.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] You cannot use it with the `new` operator or invoke the `JSON` object as a function.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] All properties and methods of `JSON` are static (just like the `Math` object).
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] JSON is a syntax for serializing objects, arrays, numbers, strings, booleans, and `null`.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] It is based upon JavaScript syntax, but is distinct from JavaScript: most of JavaScript is *not* JSON.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] Property names must be double-quoted strings; trailing commas are forbidden.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] A decimal point must be followed by at least one digit.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] Any JSON text is a valid JavaScript expression, but only after the JSON superset revision.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] Before the revision, U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR are allowed in string literals and property keys in JSON; but the same use in JavaScript string literals is a `SyntaxError`.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] Other differences include allowing only double-quoted strings and no support for `undefined` or comments.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] For those who wish to use a more human-friendly configuration format based on JSON, there is JSON5, used by the Babel compiler, and the more commonly used YAML.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] The same text may represent different values in JavaScript object literals vs.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] For more information, see Object literal syntax vs.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] Insignificant whitespace may be present anywhere except within a `JSONNumber` (numbers must contain no whitespace) or `JSONString` (where it is interpreted as the corresponding character in the string, or would cause an error).
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] The tab (U+0009), carriage return (U+000D), line feed (U+000A), and space (U+0020) characters are the only valid whitespace characters.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"JSON"`.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] This property is used in `Object.prototype.toString()`.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] Tests whether a value is an object returned by `JSON.rawJSON()`.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] Parse a piece of string text as JSON, optionally transforming the produced value and its properties, and return the value.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] Creates a "raw JSON" object containing a piece of JSON text.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] When serialized to JSON, the raw JSON object is treated as if it is already a piece of JSON.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] Return a JSON string corresponding to the specified value, optionally including only certain properties or replacing property values in a user-defined manner.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] JSON can contain number literals of arbitrary precision.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] However, it is not possible to represent all JSON numbers exactly in JavaScript, because JavaScript uses floating point representation which has a fixed precision.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] This means there is no JavaScript number that corresponds precisely to the `12345678901234567890` JSON number.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] You want to serialize it and then parse to the same exact number.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] There are, in general, two ways to ensure that numbers are losslessly converted to JSON and parsed back: one involves a JSON number, another involves a JSON string.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] JSON is a *communication format*, so if you use JSON, you are likely communicating with another system (HTTP request, storing in database, etc.).
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] The best solution to choose depends on the recipient system.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] If the recipient system does not have same JSON-handling capabilities as JavaScript, and does not support high precision numbers, you may want to serialize the number as a string, and then handle it as a string on the recipient side.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] This is also the only option in older JavaScript.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] To specify how custom data types (including `BigInt`) should be serialized to JSON, either add a `toJSON` method to your data type, or use the `replacer` function of `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] In either case, the JSON text will look like `{"gross_gdp":"12345678901234567890"}`, where the value is a string, not a number.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] Then, on the recipient side, you can parse the JSON and handle the string.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] If the recipient of this message natively supports high precision numbers (such as Python integers), passing numbers as JSON numbers is obviously better, because they can directly parse to the high precision type instead of parsing a string from JSON, and then parsing a number from the string.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] In JavaScript, you can serialize arbitrary data types to JSON numbers without producing a number value first (resulting in loss of precision) by using `JSON.rawJSON()` to precisely specify what the JSON source text should be.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] The text passed to `JSON.rawJSON` is treated as if it is already a piece of JSON, so it won't be serialized again as a string.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] This JSON can then be parsed by the recipient without any extra processing, provided that the recipient system does not have the same precision limitations as JavaScript.
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] When parsing JSON containing high-precision numbers in JavaScript, take extra care because when `JSON.parse()` invokes the `reviver` function, the value you receive is already parsed (and has lost precision).
[src:winston-logging/global-objects-json] You can use the `context.source` parameter of the `JSON.parse()` `reviver` function to re-parse the number yourself.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:winston-logging/log-file] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] In computing, **syslog** (/ˈsɪslɒɡ/) is a standard for message logging.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] It allows separation of the software that generates messages, the system that stores them, and the software that reports and analyzes them.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Each message is labeled with a facility code, indicating the type of system generating the message, and is assigned a severity level.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Computer system designers may use syslog for system management and security auditing as well as general informational, analysis, and debugging messages.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] A wide variety of devices, such as printers, routers, and message receivers across many platforms, use the syslog standard.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] This permits the consolidation of logging data from different types of systems in a central repository.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Implementations of syslog exist for many operating systems.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where a **syslog server** listens for and logs messages coming from clients.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Syslog was developed in the 1980s by Eric Allman as part of the Sendmail project.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] It was readily adopted by other applications and has since become the standard logging solution on Unix-like systems.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] A variety of implementations also exist on other operating systems and it is commonly found in network devices, such as routers.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Syslog originally functioned as a de facto standard, without any authoritative published specification, and many implementations existed, some of which were incompatible.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] The Internet Engineering Task Force documented the status quo in RFC 3164 in August 2001.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] It was standardized by RFC 5424 in March 2009.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Various companies have attempted to claim patents for specific aspects of syslog implementations.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] This has had little effect on the use and standardization of the protocol.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] The information provided by the originator of a syslog message includes the facility code and the severity level.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] The syslog software adds information to the information header before passing the entry to the syslog receiver.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Such components include an originator process ID, a timestamp, and the hostname or IP address of the device.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] A facility code is used to specify the type of system that is logging the message.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Messages with different facilities may be handled differently.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] The mapping between facility code and keyword is not uniform in different operating systems and syslog implementations.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] The meaning of severity levels other than *Emergency* and *Debug* are relative to the application.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] For example, if the purpose of the system is to process transactions to update customer account balance information, an error in the final step should be assigned *Alert* level.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] However, an error occurring in an attempt to display the ZIP code of the customer may be assigned *Error* or even *Warning* level.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] The server process that handles display of messages usually includes all lower (more severe) levels when the display of less severe levels is requested.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] That is, if messages are separated by individual severity, a *Warning* level entry will also be included when filtering for *Notice*, *Info* and *Debug* messages.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] In RFC 3164, the message component (known as MSG) was specified as having these fields: *TAG*, which should be the name of the program or process that generated the message, and *CONTENT* which contains the details of the message.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Described in RFC 5424, "MSG is what was called CONTENT in RFC 3164.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] The TAG is now part of the header, but not as a single field.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] The TAG has been split into APP-NAME, PROCID, and MSGID.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] This does not totally resemble the usage of TAG, but provides the same functionality for most of the cases." Popular syslog tools such as NXLog, Rsyslog conform to this new standard.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] The content field should be encoded in a UTF-8 character set and octet values in the traditional ASCII control character range should be avoided.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Generated log messages may be directed to various destinations, including: console, files, remote syslog servers, or relays.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Most implementations provide a command line utility, often called *logger*, as well as a software library, to send messages to the log.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] To display and monitor the collected logs, one needs to use a client application or access the log file directly on the system.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] The basic command line tools are tail and grep.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] The log servers can be configured to send the logs over the network (in addition to the local files).
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Some implementations include reporting programs for filtering and displaying syslog messages.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where the server listens on a well-known or registered port for protocol requests from clients.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Historically the most common transport layer protocol for network logging has been User Datagram Protocol (UDP), with the server listening on port 514.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Because UDP lacks congestion control mechanisms, Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 6514 is used; Transport Layer Security is also required in implementations and recommended for general use.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Since each process, application, and operating system was written independently, there is little uniformity to the payload of the log message.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] For this reason, no assumption is made about its formatting or contents.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] A syslog message is formatted (RFC 5424 gives the Augmented Backus–Naur form (ABNF) definition), but its MSG field is not.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] The network protocol is simplex communication, with no means of acknowledging the delivery to the originator.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Various groups are working on draft standards detailing the use of syslog for more than just network and security event logging, such as its proposed application within the healthcare environment.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Regulations, such as the Sarbanes–Oxley Act, PCI DSS, HIPAA, and many others, require organizations to implement comprehensive security measures, which often include collecting and analyzing logs from many different sources.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] The syslog format has proven effective in consolidating logs, as there are many open-source and proprietary tools for reporting and analysis of these logs.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Utilities exist for conversion from Windows Event Log and other log formats to syslog.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] Managed Security Service Providers attempt to apply analytical techniques and artificial intelligence algorithms to detect patterns and alert customers to problems.
[src:winston-logging/syslog] The Syslog protocol is defined by Request for Comments (RFC) documents published by the Internet Engineering Task Force (Internet standards).
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] See the Upgrade Guide for more information.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Please note that the documentation below is for `winston@3`.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] `winston` is designed to be a simple and universal logging library with support for multiple transports.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] A transport is essentially a storage device for your logs.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Each `winston` logger can have multiple transports (see: Transports) configured at different levels (see: Logging levels).
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] For example, one may want error logs to be stored in a persistent remote location (like a database), but all logs output to the console or a local file.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] `winston` aims to decouple parts of the logging process to make it more flexible and extensible.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Check out the quick start example in `./examples/`.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] There are a number of other examples in `./examples/*.js`.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Don't see an example you think should be there?
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] The recommended way to use `winston` is to create your own logger.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] You may also log directly via the default logger exposed by `require('winston')`, but this merely intended to be a convenient shared logger to use throughout your application if you so choose.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Note that the default logger doesn't have any transports by default.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] You need add transports by yourself, and leaving the default logger without any transports may produce a high memory usage issue.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] The levels provided to `createLogger` will be defined as convenience methods on the `logger` returned.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] In `winston`, both `Logger` and `Transport` instances are treated as `objectMode` streams that accept an `info` object.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] The `info` parameter provided to a given format represents a single log message.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Formats in `winston` can be accessed from `winston.format`.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] They are implemented in `logform`, a separate module from `winston`.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] This allows flexibility when writing your own transports in case you wish to include a default format with your transport.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] In modern versions of `node` template strings are very performant and are the recommended way for doing most end-user formatting.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] To see what built-in formats are available and learn more about creating your own custom logging formats, see `logform`.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Any number of formats may be combined into a single format using `format.combine`.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Since `format.combine` takes no `opts`, as a convenience it returns pre-created instance of the combined format.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] The `log` method provides the string interpolation using util.format.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Below is an example that defines a format with string interpolation of messages using `format.splat` and then serializes the entire `info` message using `format.simple`.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] If you wish to filter out a given `info` Object completely when logging then simply return a falsey value.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Use of `format.combine` will respect any falsey values return and stop evaluation of later formats in the series.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] `winston.format` is designed to be as simple as possible.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] To define a new format, simply pass it a `transform(info, opts)` function to get a new `Format`.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Each `level` is given a specific integer priority.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] The higher the priority the more important the message is considered to be, and the lower the corresponding integer priority.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] For example, as specified exactly in RFC5424 the `syslog` levels are prioritized from 0 to 7 (highest to lowest).
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] If you do not explicitly define the levels that `winston` should use, the `npm` levels above will be used.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Setting the level for your logging message can be accomplished in one of two ways.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] You can pass a string representing the logging level to the log() method or use the level specified methods defined on every winston Logger.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] `winston` allows you to define a `level` property on each transport which specifies the **maximum** level of messages that a transport should log.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] `winston` supports customizable logging levels, defaulting to npm style logging levels.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Levels must be specified at the time of creating your logger.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Although there is slight repetition in this data structure, it enables simple encapsulation if you do not want to have colors.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] This enables loggers using the `colorize` formatter to appropriately color and style the output of custom levels.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Additionally, you can also change background color and font style.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] where `winston.format.simple()` is whatever other formatter you want to use.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] The `colorize` formatter must come before any formatters adding text you wish to color.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] There are several core transports included in `winston`, which leverage the built-in networking and file I/O offered by Node.js core.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] In addition, there are additional transports written by members of the community.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] It is possible to use multiple transports of the same type e.g.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] `winston.transports.File` when you construct the transport.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] All you need to do is accept any options you need, implement a log() method, and consume it with `winston`.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] With `winston`, it is possible to catch and log `uncaughtException` events from your process.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] If you want to use this feature with the default logger, simply call `.exceptions.handle()` with a transport instance.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] By default, winston will exit after logging an uncaughtException.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] When working with custom logger instances, you can pass in separate transports to the `exceptionHandlers` property or set `handleExceptions` on any transport.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] With `winston`, it is possible to catch and log `unhandledRejection` events from your process.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] If you want to use this feature with the default logger, simply call `.rejections.handle()` with a transport instance.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] All profile messages are set to 'info' level by default, and both message and metadata are optional.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] `winston` supports querying of logs with Loggly-like options.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Specifically: `File`, `Couchdb`, `Redis`, `Loggly`, `Nssocket`, and `Http`.
[src:winston-logging/winstonjs-winston] Streaming allows you to stream your logs back from your chosen transport.
